agitated and confused, then experiences a tonic-clonic seizure. He has no known medical history and does not take any regular medications. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, his pulse rate is 120/min, blood pressure 150/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. The seizure resolves spontaneously after one minute, but he remains confused and agitated.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Administer intravenous phenytoin","Administer intravenous intralipid","Administer intravenous benzodiazepines","Administer intravenous naloxone","Administer intravenous magnesium sulfate"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient is exhibiting signs of local anaesthetic toxicity following a Bier\u0027s block, which includes central nervous system symptoms such as agitation, confusion, and seizures. The most appropriate next step in management is to administer \u003Cstrong\u003Eintravenous intralipid\u003C/strong\u003E, which acts as a lipid sink to bind the local anaesthetic and reduce its toxicity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous benzodiazepines\u003C/strong\u003E can be used to manage seizures, however as this patient\u0027s seizure has self-resolved, the more definitive treatment would take priority to prevent further deterioration. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous phenytoin\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated in this scenario as it is used for long-term seizure management rather than acute toxicity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous magnesium sulfate\u003C/strong\u003E is used for specific conditions such as eclampsia, but would not be useful for this patient with local anaesthetic toxicity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous naloxone\u003C/strong\u003E is an opioid antagonist and is not relevant in the context of local anaesthetic toxicity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPrompt recognition and treatment of local anaesthetic toxicity are crucial to prevent further complications, including cardiovascular collapse.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Local anaesthetic toxicity can occur after a Bier\u0027s block and requires prompt recognition and management.","Symptoms of local anaesthetic toxicity include CNS and cardiovascular manifestations such as seizures, altered mental status, and arrhythmias.","Intralipid therapy is a key treatment for severe local anaesthetic toxicity."],"references":["Mahajan A, Derian A. Local Anesthetic Toxicity. In: StatPearls Publishing. 2022. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK499964/","Sekimoto K, Tobe M, Saito S. Local anesthetic toxicity: acute and chronic management. Acute Med Surg. 2017 Mar 6;4(2):152-160. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5667269/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38098"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14128"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38098","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/38098"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-09T12:35:48+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-09T12:36:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6808"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52729"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{